## 4. Typography

Typography must be clear, functional, and thematically appropriate. We use two main font styles.

### 4.1. Display Font
-   **Style:** A geometric sans-serif with a slightly condensed profile and squared-off terminals. Think "engraved" or "stenciled." It should feel engineered and precise.
-   **Usage:** Headlines, titles, major UI callouts (e.g., button text), and world-space signage.
-   **Example Families:** Roboto Mono, Oswald, or a custom font inspired by mechanical schematics.

### 4.2. Text Font
-   **Style:** A highly legible, humanist sans-serif. It should be clean, open, and comfortable to read in long-form paragraphs.
-   **Usage:** Body copy, descriptions, subtitles, and smaller UI labels.
-   **Example Families:** Inter, Source Sans Pro, Lato.

### 4.3. On-Screen Text Safety Guidelines
All critical text and UI elements must adhere to the following safe zones to ensure visibility on all displays.

-   **Title Safe Area:** 90% of the screen. All critical text must remain within this inner 90% boundary.
-   **Action Safe Area:** 85% of the screen. All interactive elements (buttons, icons) must be fully contained within this boundary to prevent accidental cropping.

